Demo: trinidi.reconstruct Module¶

This script illustrates the functionality of the trinidi.reconstruct submodule.

In [2]:
import numpy as np

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

from trinidi import cross_section, reconstruct, resolution, util

Generation of Simulated data¶

We use the function below to generate the data. The details of this function are not necessarily important for the user to understand.

In [3]:
def generate_sample_data(
    isotopes,
    z,
    t=0.90,
    t_0=72,
    t_last=400,
    flight_path_length=10,
    projection_shape=(31, 31),
    kernels=None,
    acquisition_time=10,
):
    r"""Generate example data."""

    t_A = np.arange(t_0, t_last, t)
    N_A = t_A.size

    if not kernels:
        kernels = [np.array([1]), np.array([1 / 4, 1 / 4, 1 / 4, 1 / 4])]

    output_shape = projection_shape + (N_A,)

    R = resolution.ResolutionOperator(output_shape, t_A, kernels=kernels)
    t_F = R.t_F

    , b, , _1, _2 = util.generate_spectra(t_A, acquisition_time=10)
    N_b = .size

    D = cross_section.XSDict(isotopes, t_F, flight_path_length)

    Z = util.rose_phantom(projection_shape[0], num_circles=z.size, radius=2 / 3) * z.reshape(
        [1, 1, z.size]
    )

    v = np.random.poisson(1000, size=projection_shape + (1,))
    v = v / v.mean()

     = v @ .T
    B = v @ b.T

    Y_o_bar =  + B
    Y_s_bar = _1 * ( * R(np.exp(-Z @ D.values)) + _2 * B)

    Y_o = np.random.poisson(Y_o_bar)
    Y_s = np.random.poisson(Y_s_bar)

    ground_truth_params = {"z": z, "_1": _1, "_2": _2, "": }

    return Y_o, Y_s, ground_truth_params, Z, t_A, flight_path_length, N_b, kernels

Below we define what isotopes to use for the phantom and what their corresponding densities should become.

In [4]:
isotopes = ["U-238", "Pu-239", "Ta-181"]
z = np.array([[0.005, 0.003, 0.004]]).T


# projection_shape = (20, 20) # use this for fast execution
projection_shape = (60, 60)  # use this for the docs

Y_o, Y_s, ground_truth_params, Z, t_A, flight_path_length, N_b, kernels = generate_sample_data(
    isotopes, z, acquisition_time=10, projection_shape=projection_shape
)

The arrays Y_o and Y_s contain the the open beam and sample neutron count measurements. The first (two) axes correspond to projection_shape, which in most cases is equal to the detector shape. The last axis correponds to the time-of-arrival (TOA) dimension which has N_A bins.

We can show the areal densities Z using the plotting function below. The phantom consists of several discs and disc i has the density z[i] and corresponds to isotope[i].

In [9]:
def plot_densities(fig, ax, Z, isotopes, vmaxs=None):
    r"""Show areal densities. `ax` must be list."""

    for i, isotope in enumerate(isotopes):
        z = Z[:, :, i]
        if vmaxs is None:
            vmax = np.percentile(z, 99.9)
        else:
            vmax = vmaxs[i]
        vmin = 0
        im = ax[i].imshow(z, vmin=vmin, vmax=vmax)
        fig.colorbar(im, ax=ax[i], format="%.1e")
        ax[i].set_title(f"{isotope}")
        ax[i].axis("off")

    fig.suptitle("Areal Densities [mol/cm]")

    return fig, ax


fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, N_m, figsize=[12, 3.3])

plt.show()

Preparation for the Reconstruction¶

For the reconstruction we need to define the regions _z and _0 that correspond to the uniformly dense region and the open beam region, respectively.

For this we use the ProjectionRegion class. We initialize it with a mask (boolean array) that is of shape projection_shape + (1,), indicating which pixels belong to these regions.

In this example we use the ground truth Z to find these regions as

  • the overlap of all discs (_z)
  • the complement of the union of all discs (_0).

(In the case when the ground truth is not known, the user will have to find a way to define these regions.)

In [10]:
_z = reconstruct.ProjectionRegion(np.prod(Z, axis=2, keepdims=True) > 0)
_0 = reconstruct.ProjectionRegion(np.sum(Z, axis=2, keepdims=True) == 0)

We can illustrate these regions using the builtin ProjectionRegion.plot_contour function and the ProjectionRegion.imshow function below.

In [11]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=[14, 4])
ax = np.atleast_1d(ax)

ax[0].imshow(np.sum(Y_s, axis=-1) / np.sum(Y_o, axis=-1), vmin=0)
ax[0].set_title("1Y_s / 1Y_o (TOF integrated measurement ratio)")
_z.plot_contours(ax[0], color="red")
_0.plot_contours(ax[0], color="blue")

_z.imshow(ax[1], title="_z")
_0.imshow(ax[2], title="_0")

plt.show()

Next we need to define the resolution operator, R. We use the same kernels used for the generation of the data to initialize the ResolutioOperator object.

In [12]:
R = resolution.ResolutionOperator(Y_s.shape, t_A, kernels=kernels)
print(R)

    projection_shape = (60, 60)

Since the resolution operator inputs wider spectra than it outputs, there is an additional vector of time-of-flights (TOF), t_F, with size N_F. The t_F array is calibrated such that approximately R(t_A) = t_F.

Reconstruction of the Nuisance Parameters¶

We define a ParameterEstimator object. For the background we use the same number N_b of basis functions. This estimates the nuisance parameters (z, _1, _1, ). Novice users do not need to worry about the values and handling of these parameters.

In [16]:
par = reconstruct.ParameterEstimator(Y_o, Y_s, R, D, _z, _0=_0, N_b=N_b)

Advanced users: The parameters are available through the ParameterEstimator.get function.

In [17]:
d = par.get()
print(d)

{'z': array([[0.00493508],
       [0.0030051 ],
       [0.00395889]]), '_1': 1.19643529937546, '_2': 0.8045250689291287, '': array([[46.53269903],
       [-8.85697955],
       [ 0.36649002]])}

Advanced users: The parameters can manually be modified using the ParameterEstimator.set function. We also provide similar save and load functions to write/read them to file.

In [18]:
par.set(**d)
par.set(z=d["z"], _1=d["_1"], _2=d["_2"], =d[""])  # same as line above

# par.save("par.npy")
# d = par.load("par.npy")

Reconstruction of the Areal Densities¶

We use this simple plotting function below to keep things clean.

In [22]:
def plot_compare(Z, str_Z, Z_hat, str_Z_hat):
    r"""Generate two plots comparing ground truth with reconstruction."""
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, N_m, figsize=[12, 3.3])
    ax = np.atleast_1d(ax)
    plot_densities(fig, ax, Z, isotopes, vmaxs=z * 1.5)
    fig.suptitle(f"{str_Z} [mol/cm]")

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, N_m, figsize=[12, 3.3])
    ax = np.atleast_1d(ax)
    plot_densities(fig, ax, Z_hat, isotopes, vmaxs=z * 1.5)
    fig.suptitle(f"{str_Z_hat} [mol/cm]")

We define a DensityEstimator object. Note that if the optional arguments D and R are left empty, the D and R operators from the par Parameters object will be used for the reconstruction.

(If different D and R operators are desired, they need to be passed to the DensityEstimator constructor.)

In [23]:
den = reconstruct.DensityEstimator(Y_s, par, non_negative_Z=False, dispperiod=50)

We reonstruct the areal densities using the DensityEstimator.solve function.

Cropped or Binned Measurements¶

In practice, it is not always desired to reconstruct the full field of view or at full resolution. For this reason we provide the projection_transform argument in the DensityEstimator constructor. Perhaps we require the full field of view to estimate the nuisance parameters, but we only want to reconstruct a small cropped region.

The projection_transform is the desired operation that is applied to the measurements and used internally to handle the modification of the background and flux estimates.

First we show an example of binned data using the below defined binning_2x2 function.

In [27]:
def binning_2x2(Y):
    r"""Bin an array of shape (N, M, ...) with the result being (N//2, M//2, ...)"""
    N0 = Y.shape[0] // 2
    N1 = Y.shape[1] // 2
    Y = Y[0::2][:N0] + Y[1::2][:N0]
    Y = Y[:, 0::2][:, :N1] + Y[:, 1::2][:, :N1]
    return Y

We define the DensityEstimator but pass the binning_2x2 as the projection_transform argument and use solve as usual. Note that the resulting detector shape is half the size in each direction.

In [28]:
den = reconstruct.DensityEstimator(
    Y_s, par, projection_transform=binning_2x2, non_negative_Z=False, dispperiod=50
)
den.solve(iterations=200)

Z_binned = binning_2x2(Z) / (2 * 2)  # over 4 to keep ground truth scale the same.
Z_hat_binned = den.Z

print(f"{Z.shape = }")
print(f"{Z_binned.shape = }")

Second we show an example of cropping data using the below defined crop function and the same

In [30]:
def crop(Y):
    r"""Create center crop from 1/5 to 4/5 of the FOV."""
    N0 = Y.shape[0] // 5
    N1 = Y.shape[1] // 5
    Y = Y[N0 : 4 * N0, N1 : 4 * N1]
    return Y


den = reconstruct.DensityEstimator(
    Y_s, par, projection_transform=crop, non_negative_Z=False, dispperiod=50
)
den.solve(iterations=200)

Z_crop = crop(Z)
Z_hat_crop = den.Z

print(f"{Z_crop.shape = }")
print(f"{Z.shape = }")


plot_compare(Z_crop, "Cropped Ground Truth", Z_hat_crop, "Reconstruction from Cropped Measurement")
plt.show()
